      <data key="d4">["1"]</data>
      <data key="d7">Deon's concern; reason task remains tentatively with Deon pending priority review</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0002">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Cumulus's approach to pseudonymization is vague; they likely do not yet have a firm plan</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "I think they don't know what they're going to do, to be honest. ... he said he, John says he comes up with suggestions and then the data scientists suggest other stuff.", "ts": 955, "source": "chapter_2"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["2"]</data>
      <data key="d7">Laura and Deon's shared assessment; reason for insisting on ground truth evaluation framework</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0003">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Without ground truth, third-party vendors produce proof-of-concept work of unknown quality</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "if you don't give them ground truth, they'll just do like a kind of proof of concept thing that you don't even know if it works well or not. So you end up doing everything again.", "ts": 975, "source": "chapter_2"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["2"]</data>
      <data key="d7">Laura's experience with third parties; justification for ground truth collection work</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0004">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">NICE guideline data is effectively publicly available (accessible on NICE website), reducing compliance concern</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "it's publicly available data or it's like fairly available data. Or you can look up all the nice guidelines like on their website. This is just an API form of it.", "ts": 1300, "source": "chapter_3"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["3"]</data>
      <data key="d7">Deon's view; used to support sharing API key temporarily</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0005">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Cumulus will deliver code transparently and Medbrief engineers can extend and reuse it</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "they'll give us the code and we can even use it for other projects and like the nice guidelines. ... they were actually quite deliberate in saying that because they were like happy that we had engineers", "ts": 1580, "source": "chapter_3"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["3"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0006">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Third parties often recommend the newest or most expensive Azure services regardless of suitability</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "they end up giving us a service that's like the newest one that Azure has in the market because they want to have more use cases with that or the one that's more costly or whatever and you end up having something that it's not scalable or you don't even know how to use it", "ts": 1645, "source": "Laura Gongas"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["4"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0007">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">The team lacks data engineering expertise and cannot critically evaluate Cumulus's data architecture claims</data>
      <data key="d2">0.95</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "we don't have anyone in the team that has a data engineering formation. So, if they tell us we're using Databricks and Azure Data Factory and this lake, we just believe them", "ts": 1622, "source": "Laura Gongas"}, {"quote": "with the AI side, I feel comfortable. But with the data side, they could just be selling us whatever.", "ts": 1993, "source": "Laura Gongas"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["4"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0008">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Rowan is not a data engineering expert and has not used these tools himself</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "I'm also not a data engineering expert and so building these tools I have not used myself.", "ts": 1700, "source": "Rowan Reid"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["4"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0009">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Rowan having time to investigate the data engineering stack is the most important thing his team is currently lacking</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "just having that time to look into it is what your team is lacking at the moment, Laoura", "ts": 2035, "source": "Deon Kuhn"}]</data>
      <data key="d4">["5"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="artifact:gf0001">
      <data key="d0">Artifact</data>
      <data key="d1">Azure Key Vault (proposed NICE API key storage)</data>
      <data key="d9">Deon proposes storing the NICE API key in Azure Key Vault so Cumulus can use it programmatically without being able to view or extract it, as a potential compliance mitigation.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "If you pop that key in the key vault so that they can't view it, but they can use it, that's possible, right, with Azure as far as I know. So they're going to use it in our infrastructure.", "ts": 354, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0002">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">NICE may charge non-UK users for API access, adding a financial compliance dimension</data>
      <data key="d10">Laura asserts NICE charges users outside the UK, which would make sharing the key with Cumulus (non-UK based) a compliance and financial issue beyond just access eligibility.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "they do have, I think they charge people that are outside of the UK or something like that. So I think. We might want to look into that with Brendan", "ts": 373, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0003">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Entity types in clinical guidelines and clinical case records are expected to be the same</data>
      <data key="d10">Laura states that the entity types Cumulus would extract from clinical case records will likely be identical to those needed from NICE guidelines, making the two pipeline tracks complementary rather than divergent.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "we need them to be able to extract the entities from the guidelines, which are going to be probably the same entities as the ones in the clinical records.", "ts": 449, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0004">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Cumulus planned to focus on a narrow case type (e.g. obstetrics) to limit the NICE guidelines scope</data>
      <data key="d10">Deon recalls Cumulus described wanting to focus on a particular clinical speciality (citing obstetrics as an example) in order to reduce the number of NICE guidelines they would need to query or process.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "they also said they wanted to focus on a particular kind of case, like obstetrics or whatever, and I think that was also to reduce the number of nice guidelines that they would potentially need to query or look up.", "ts": 434, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0005">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Cumulus will reveal more about their technical approach once the engagement formally starts</data>
      <data key="d10">Deon reports that Cumulus stated they will share and discuss more detail about their planned implementation once the engagement has formally begun, giving Medbrief input at that stage.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "once we start the engagement, they're going to reveal more, discuss more about how they're planning to do stuff, so that we also have input on that.", "ts": 502, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0006">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Only two cases are needed for the initial ground truth annotation exercise</data>
      <data key="d10">Laura states that Cumulus indicated only two cases are required for the initial ground truth dataset, implying the annotation effort is manageable in scope.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:02"]</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "They said they only needed two, so it shouldn't be that difficult.", "ts": 189, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0007">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Clinicians cannot annotate ground truth cases during their billable working hours</data>
      <data key="d10">Laura notes a practical scheduling constraint: clinicians cannot perform ground truth annotation at the same time as their paid clinical work, so annotation must happen after their shifts end.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:05"]</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "we can't do it at the same time because they're in their billable hours, when they're done with that, they'll be able to look into the thumbs down messages and give us a bit more of detail as to why it was incorrect", "ts": 648, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="action:gf0008">
      <data key="d0">ActionItem</data>
      <data key="d1">Deon to investigate anomalous expert profile instances created via direct profile update (scheduled for Friday)</data>
      <data key="d9">Deon identifies that some experts have been created through the system via direct profile updates, which should not be possible. He was scheduled to investigate these instances on Friday but had not yet done so at time of meeting.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:01"]</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "some experts have been created through the system, which where they've gone in and updated their profiles, which shouldn't be the case, so I'll need to have a look at those. I'm meant to do it on Friday, but I don't have time why those instances have been created, but anyway.", "ts": 82, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0009">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Data architecture review is worthwhile regardless of whether Cumulus is ultimately engaged</data>
      <data key="d10">Even if Medbrief does not accept Cumulus's proposal, reviewing their proposed data architecture is still valuable because Medbrief will need to build the same stack with or without Cumulus.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:04"]</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "even if we don't, I think it's still useful to look into this because we are still going to build it with them or without them. So we still need to look into it.", "ts": 1965, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="artifact:gf0010">
      <data key="d0">Artifact</data>
      <data key="d1">Expert Match AI ingestion endpoint — three-table structure (expert, case, case-expert)</data>
      <data key="d9">Laura specifies that the ingestion endpoint covers three distinct tables: an expert table, a case table, and a case-expert relationship table. This structural detail is load-bearing for understanding which events must trigger a sync call.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:01"]</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "you'll see that we have an expert table, a case table, and a case expert table. And that's something that you can see from the endpoint.", "ts": 143, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0011">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Medbrief could ingest NICE guidelines itself and supply the resulting JSON directly to Cumulus, avoiding the API key sharing problem</data>
      <data key="d10">Laura proposes an alternative to giving Cumulus the NICE API key: Medbrief performs the NICE ingestion internally and then hands Cumulus the structured JSON output, so Cumulus never needs direct API access.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "we might want to do that ourselves and just give them the output of the queries, like exactly how we got the result from nice, but just giving them the JSONs.", "ts": 349, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0012">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Cumulus quoted the engagement at 10 weeks; Deon's internal estimate is 6 to 8 weeks</data>
      <data key="d10">During the NICE API key discussion Deon references the engagement duration as six to eight weeks, but notes that Cumulus themselves stated ten weeks, indicating a discrepancy in timeline expectations.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "for the duration of the work, so for the six to 8 weeks, I know they say 10 weeks, but for the duration of the work", "ts": 361, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0013">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">The safest Cumulus scope is entity extraction only; NICE guideline processing should be excluded from the current engagement</data>
      <data key="d10">Deon recommends that the safest path is to remove NICE guideline work from the Cumulus scope entirely and focus only on entity extraction from case data, because Cumulus's intentions for the guidelines are unclear and entity extraction is the most important deliverable.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "the safest path again here, like Laoura described, would be to avoid the NICE guideline in this instance and just go with the entity extraction, because that's the most important part. Because we, I have no idea what they're playing with the the nice guidelines according to this either.", "ts": 504, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0014">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Rowan working with other devs on Expert Match would create distraction, justifying keeping him focused on Cumulus work</data>
      <data key="d10">Beyond the prior-knowledge concern (claim:0001), Deon adds a second distinct reason for retaking the Expert Match task: requiring Rowan to coordinate closely with other developers would pull him away from the focused data engineering investigation the team most needs from him right now.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:05"]</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "needing to like work too much with the other devs on stuff like that might just distract the situation. So I'll take that one for the team for this for now.", "ts": 2076, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="decision:gf0015">
      <data key="d0">Decision</data>
      <data key="d1">Explicit priority order: ground truth collection first (clinician time is bottleneck), data strategy last (longer-term)</data>
      <data key="d10">Laura states the priority ordering explicitly at the close of the meeting: starting ground truth collection is the single most important item because it depends on clinician availability and will take the most calendar time; the data strategy work is deprioritised as a longer-horizon task.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:05"]</data>
      <data key="d3">[{"quote": "I think there's things that are more priority than others, like obviously the data strategy is something that will take more time, but the starting to collect the ground truth, that's actually the most important one because it will take time for clinicians to do it, so the sooner that we have the stuff for them, the better.", "ts": 1988, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:01">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Expert Match Storage Endpoint Integration</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:01"]</data>
      <data key="d11">1</data>
      <data key="d12">Laura opens with a request for the dev team to call the AI ingestion endpoint whenever an expert or case is created, updated, or deleted — removing the need for manual sync. The team discusses the update queue table, cache invalidation, and whether this task should sit with Deon or Rowan.</data>
      <data key="d13">0.0</data>
      <data key="d14">480.0</data>
      <data key="d15">[]</data>
      <data key="d16">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:02">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Cumulus Scope and Pseudonymization Ground Truth</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:02"]</data>
      <data key="d11">2</data>
      <data key="d12">Laura introduces the Cumulus partnership scope: entity extraction and pseudonymization. The team agrees they need to create their own ground truth (via clinician annotation of deceased-patient cases) to evaluate Cumulus's output, and discusses tooling for annotation and pre-population with AI to reduce clinician burden.</data>
      <data key="d13">480.0</data>
      <data key="d14">1050.0</data>
      <data key="d15">[]</data>
      <data key="d16">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:03">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Cumulus Flow Diagram and NICE API Compliance</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d11">3</data>
      <data key="d12">Laura shares her screen showing Cumulus's proposed pipeline: guideline structuring (NICE) and case entity extraction running in parallel before feeding a reasoning layer. The team debates NICE API key sharing, compliance (UK-based requirement), and whether to let Cumulus use the key via Azure Key Vault or to ingest NICE guidelines internally and hand Cumulus the JSON output.</data>
      <data key="d13">1050.0</data>
      <data key="d14">1620.0</data>
      <data key="d15">[]</data>
      <data key="d16">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:04">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Data Architecture Review and Rowan's Onboarding</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:04"]</data>
      <data key="d11">4</data>
      <data key="d12">Laura asks Rowan to review Cumulus's data architecture proposal (Databricks, Azure Data Factory, Data Lake) and assess whether it is fit for purpose, citing concerns about vendors upselling costly or non-scalable services. Deon suggests using the enterprise skills development platform. Rowan is candid about his limited data engineering tool experience but commits to applying his judgement.</data>
      <data key="d13">1620.0</data>
      <data key="d14">2000.0</data>
      <data key="d15">[]</data>
      <data key="d16">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:05">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Priorities, Human-in-the-Loop, and Closing Decisions</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d3">[]</data>
      <data key="d4">["chapter:05"]</data>
      <data key="d11">5</data>
      <data key="d12">The team wraps up remaining items: Sally integration stays with Deon; human-in-the-loop (thumbs up/down for Ask Alex chat) is Dave's ticket but Rowan may help with data collation later; Deon takes back the storage endpoint task after assessing it requires too much context for Rowan to ramp on right now. Final priority order: Cumulus ground truth, data architecture review, then ongoing sprint work.</data>
      <data key="d13">2000.0</data>
      <data key="d14">2265.28</data>
      <data key="d15">[]</data>
